                            <comment id="12641363" author="noble.paul" created="Tue, 21 Oct 2008 12:59:36 +0100"  >&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;added an option for replicateafter startup&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;fixed issues w/ registering the listeners&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12642072" author="shalinmangar" created="Thu, 23 Oct 2008 07:21:08 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;This was accidentally committed with the &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SOLR-561&quot; title=&quot;Solr replication by Solr (for windows also)&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SOLR-561&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SOLR-561&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; fixes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m marking this issue as resolved. We can re-open it if we find a problem.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12663533" author="mhenson" created="Tue, 13 Jan 2009 23:24:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have not been able to get this to work in my configuration. The slave instance, starting with an empty target directory, creates segments files for itself on startup. It then has an &quot;index version&quot; that is a higher number than the master&apos;s index version. The replication never starts, unless I do a commit on the master.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My replication config is very straightforward. My configuration assumes that the slave machine is starting off completely empty of all data (aside from the essentials necessary to get Solr to start), and will pull everything from the master instance.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;NOTE: I tested this with nightly build solr-2009-01-12.zip&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12664246" author="shalinmangar" created="Thu, 15 Jan 2009 20:28:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for reporting this Michael. I&apos;ll try to reproduce the issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12668953" author="pwolanin" created="Fri, 30 Jan 2009 17:50:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Jacob and I are seeing the exact same issue today - is there some way to set the timestamp in the index on the slave server ?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12668989" author="noble.paul" created="Fri, 30 Jan 2009 19:24:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;is the version on the master showing zero?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12668996" author="noble.paul" created="Fri, 30 Jan 2009 19:49:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;An untested patch. can you try it out?&lt;br/&gt;
When there are no commits on the master the list of files associated with the current commit point is not avalable because onCommit/onInit is not called on the deletionpolicy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So if we do a force open of the writer , the onInit() gets called on the deletionpolicy and we get a chance to read the file names&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12668998" author="shalinmangar" created="Fri, 30 Jan 2009 19:52:40 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Re-opening to investigate/fix problems reported on this feature.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12669686" author="akshay" created="Mon, 2 Feb 2009 18:57:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch in sync with trunk. This is working now. Do we need a test case for this Shalin?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12670300" author="shalinmangar" created="Wed, 4 Feb 2009 10:33:25 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed revision 740678.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks Akshay. I&apos;ll keep the issue open until we can add a test.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12671025" author="akshay" created="Fri, 6 Feb 2009 07:17:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch with test case.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12671027" author="shalinmangar" created="Fri, 6 Feb 2009 07:23:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed revision 741451.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks Akshay!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12775557" author="gsingers" created="Tue, 10 Nov 2009 15:51:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Bulk close for Solr 1.4&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
